Model Building

We fitted a Bayesian Generalised Additive Model (GAM) in brms (BÃ¼rkner 2017â€“2021) to explain geometric-mean chlorophyll-a (GeoMean_Chla) across 10 sites. To improve convergence and account for differing scales, both the response and all five environmental drivers (SST, IceCover, Mean_WindSpeed_Above10, Freq_WindSpeed_Above10, WindSpeed) were standardized (z-scored) prior to modelling. The standardized response was then modelled with a Studentâ€™s t likelihood for robustness to outliers, and each predictor entered as a thin-plate spline with region-specific smooths. Basic weakly-informative priors were used throughout.

Posterior inference used NUTS with 4 chains of 5 000 iterations (500 warm-up). All Rhat â‰¤1.01 and effective sample sizes > 1 000, indicating good convergence.
